<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910128-0119</DOCNO><DOCID>910128-0119.</DOCID><HL>   Operation PUSH Is Forced   To Lay Off 12-Person Staff</HL><DATE>01/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   NKE</CO><IN>TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)</IN><LP>   CHICAGO -- Operation PUSH, a civil rights group founded bythe Rev. Jesse Jackson, laid off its 12-person staff lastweek because of problems raising money.   PUSH, which stands for People United to Serve Humanity,was founded in 1971 and headed by Mr. Jackson until he took aleave of absence to run for the U.S. presidency in 1983. Mr.Jackson still serves on its board.</LP><TEXT>   At its peak in the late 1970s, PUSH employed 120 people.Its focus has been on demanding equal opportunities forminorities in the private sector. It currently iscoordinating a boycott against Nike Inc., which the Rev.Willie Barrow, PUSH vice chairman, says the organizationplans to continue. A spokesperson for the Beaverton,Ore.-based sneaker maker declined comment on whether theboycott has had any effect on the company.   PUSH's annual budget of $1.5 million comes from acombination of private contributions, membership fees andfund-raisers. Ms. Barrow attributed the organization'sfinancial problems to the recent downturn in the economy. &quot;Inspite of it all, PUSH is going to survive and remain open,&quot;says Ms. Barrow. She says PUSH will continue to operate witha volunteer staff until it can raise the money to pay them.</TEXT></DOC>